<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="ab063345-aa06-5e65-99f7-91a6e49f3e95" activityNameId="d6f08daa-1c9b-415e-98ad-c10de62c1a5c" parentActivityId="0049f382-44ea-5ae9-bc63-6717d60da248" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">ethoxylated alcohol (AE7) production, petrochemical</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">alcohol ethoxylate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Fatty Alcohol Ethoxylate</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From reception of fatty alcohol from petrochemicals, ethylene oxide, and nitrogen at the factory gate.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with 1 kg of ethoxylated alcohol (AE7). The dataset includes the processing of the material inputs, the consumption of energy, the use of infrastructure, the production of waste, and emissions to water and air. The dataset doesn't include water consumption.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of ethoxylated alcohol with seven polyether units (AE7) from C12-C15 fatty alcohol derived from petrochemicals. AE7 is one type of alcohol ethoxylate (AE).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Alcohol ethoxylates are the largest group within the class of nonionic tensides. The hydrophobic part is formed by fatty alcohols with chain lengths from C9-C18. The hydrophilic part consists of a polyether chain formed by condensation of ethylene oxide to the fatty alcohol. Several hundred different AE are commercially available, differing by alcohol structure and number of polyether units. The generic chemical structure of AE is:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">CH3-(CH2)n-CHR-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)m-OH (n = 5-15, m = 2-100, R = H or n-alkyl)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Because of their structural variety, AE have very different physical and chemical properties. In comparison with other tensides like anionic surfactants, alcohol ethoxylates exhibit a better fat soil removal capacity, especially at low temperatures. AE7 is mainly used in the detergents industry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">AE are produced by the reaction of fatty alcohols with ethylene oxide, leading to a condensation of polyethylene glycolether groups on the alcohol chains. The production of AE is described on the following flow diagram:</text>
          <imageUrl index="5">https://db3.ecoinvent.org/images/b688cb9c-081a-4ad4-b2a5-92bd709ae553</imageUrl>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">The fatty alcohols can be derived from petrochemicals, palm kernel, or coconut oil. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">In this dataset, the material and energy inputs are based on literature sources, the water consumption is estimated based on data from a large chemical plant (Gendorf 2016). The production of waste and emissions to water and air are calculated based on literature sources.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Zah R., Hischier R. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Detergents. ecoinvent report No. 12. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, 2007.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="68009ca2-60ee-4d5c-a36d-125adbe838a7">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2023:Manufacture of soap and detergents, cleaning and polishing preparations, pe</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data based on the European ethoxylated alcohols production. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="2">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Alcohol ethoxylates (AE) are produced by the reaction of fatty alcohols with ethylene oxide leading to a condensation of polyethylene glycolether groups on the alcohol chains. The fatty alcohols can be derived from petrochemical, palm kernel, or coconut oil. The reaction takes place at temperatures ranging from 150°C to 200°C. The grade of ethoxylation, e.g. the specific number of polyether units condensed to the alcohol chains, is controlled by the concentration of ethylene oxid in the ethoxylation process. The petrochemical route has been designated as modern technology, since it has the best ability to change capacity with changes in demand. This is an average technology for the production of AE representing typical European production mix in the mid 90s.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reference:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Schul W. (1995) A Life-Cycle Inventory for the Production of Detergent Range Alcohol Ethoxylates in Europe. In: Tenside, Surfactants, Detergents, 32(2), pp. 171-192.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Stalmans M., Berenbold H., Berna J. L., Cavalli L., Dillarstone A., Franke M., Hirsinger F., Janzen D., Kosswig K., Postlethwaite D., Rappert T., Renta C., Scharer D., Schick K.-P., Schul W., Thomas H. and Sloten R. V. (1995) European Life-Cycle Inventory for Detergent Surfactants Production. In: Tenside, Surfactants, Detergents, 32(2), pp. 84-109</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1992-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Date of published literature. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="af216d6d-e292-50df-8bc0-798cd87a7bf0" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="ee02b2e7-9c42-4fe3-904b-2a4a6f221656" productionVolumeAmount="1766100.0" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">ethoxylated alcohol (AE7)</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Alcohol Ethoxylates (AE) are molecules with an hydrophobic and an hydrophilic part. The hydrophobic part is formed by fatty alcohols with chain lengths from C9-C18. The hydrophilic part consists of a polyether chain formed by condensation of ethylene oxide to the fatty alcohol. Several hundred different AE are commercially available, differing by alcohol structure and number of polyether units. The generic chemical structure of AE is:
CH3-(CH2)n-CHR-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)m-OH
(n = 5-15, m = 2-100, R = H or n-alkyl)
AE7 have an average value of seven polyether units (m = 7). 
Alcohol Ethoxylates (AE) are the largest group within the class of nonionic tensides. In comparison with other tensides like anionic surfactants, alcohol ethoxylates exhibit a better fat soil removal capacity, especially at low temperatures.</comment>
        <property propertyId="f2283db2-62e4-467f-b9ac-c4f45be563b4" amount="0.643326969974121" isDefiningValue="false" isCalculatedAmount="false" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
          <name xml:lang="en">carbon allocation</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        </property>
        <property propertyId="a301a838-7975-4d89-9e74-8eb77ad03cd1" amount="0.643326969974121" isDefiningValue="false" isCalculatedAmount="false" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
          <name xml:lang="en">carbon content</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
        </property>
        <property propertyId="c74c3729-e577-4081-b572-a283d2561a75" amount="0.643326969974121" isDefiningValue="false" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
          <name xml:lang="en">carbon content, fossil</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
          <comment xml:lang="en">The generic chemical structure of AE is: CH3-(CH2)n-CHR-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)m-OH (n = 5-15, m = 2-100, R = H or n-alkyl). AE are produced by the reaction of fatty alcohols with ethylene oxide leading to a condensation of polyethylene glycolether groups on the alcohol chains (ecoinvent report 12-part 4). Fatty alcohols were considered to have an average length of C14. Ethoxylated alcohol (AE7) has an average value of seven polyether units (AE7) (ecoinvent report 12-part 4). The formula that has then been used to calculate the C content of the products is CH3-(CH2)11-CH2-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)7-OH. In this molecule, all C has a fossile origin, as fatty alcohols are produced from petrochemical oil</comment>
        </property>
        <property propertyId="6393c14b-db78-445d-a47b-c0cb866a1b25" amount="0.0" isDefiningValue="false" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
          <name xml:lang="en">carbon content, non-fossil</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
          <comment xml:lang="en">The generic chemical structure of AE is: CH3-(CH2)n-CHR-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)m-OH (n = 5-15, m = 2-100, R = H or n-alkyl). AE are produced by the reaction of fatty alcohols with ethylene oxide leading to a condensation of polyethylene glycolether groups on the alcohol chains (ecoinvent report 12-part 4). Fatty alcohols were considered to have an average length of C14. Ethoxylated alcohol (AE7) has an average value of seven polyether units (AE7) (ecoinvent report 12-part 4). The formula that has then been used to calculate the C content of the products is CH3-(CH2)11-CH2-CH2-(O-CH2-CH2)7-OH. In this molecule, all C has a fossile origin, as fatty alcohols are produced from petrochemical oil</comment>
        </property>
        <property propertyId="3a0af1d6-04c3-41c6-a3da-92c4f61e0eaa" amount="1.0" isDefiningValue="false" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
